# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anindilyakwa-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Australian languages have historically been classified into numerous language families.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Despite the diversity of Australian languages, many linguists have considered for decades that most languages of the Australian continent, including Pama-Nyungan, are members of one higher-level family.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] A proto-language, Proto-Australian, was reconstructed for the first time in 2024.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Proto-Australian is dated to approximately 6,000 years before the present, much later than human habitation of Australia; how it spread across the continent, replacing earlier languages, is as yet unclear.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] There have always been some Australian languages excluded from larger groupings as language isolates; currently, Tiwi and the Tasmanian languages are considered unrelated to Proto-Australian.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Of the languages of the Torres Strait, Kala Lagaw Ya is a Pama-Nyungan language, while Meriam Mer is a Papuan language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] At the start of the 21st century, fewer than 150 Aboriginal languages remained in daily use, with the majority being highly endangered.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2020, 90 percent of the barely more than 100 languages still spoken are considered endangered.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Thirteen languages are still being acquired by children.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The surviving languages are located in the most isolated areas.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Of the five least endangered Western Australian Aboriginal languages, four belong to the Western Desert grouping of the Central and Great Victoria Desert.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2026 the most widely-spoken languages by Australian Aboriginal people are those whose origins post-date the colonisation of Australia; these languages include Australian Kriol, Australian Aboriginal English, and Light Warlpiri.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The Indigenous languages of Australia number in the hundreds, the precise number being quite uncertain, although there is a range of estimates from a minimum of around 250 up to possibly 363.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2020, 90 per cent of the barely more than 100 languages still spoken are considered endangered.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Yolŋu languages from north-east Arnhem Land are also currently learned by children.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Bilingual education is being used successfully in some communities.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Seven of the most widely spoken Australian languages, such as Warlpiri, Murrinh-patha and Tiwi, retain between 1,000 and 3,000 speakers.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some Indigenous communities and linguists show support for learning programmes either for language revival proper or for only "post-vernacular maintenance" (Indigenous communities having the opportunity to learn some words and concepts related to the lost language).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The *National Indigenous Languages Survey* is a regular Australia-wide survey of the status of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander languages conducted in 2005, 2014 and 2019.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Total 47 languages, 42,300 speakers, with 11 having only approximately 100.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Most Australian languages are commonly held to belong to the Pama–Nyungan family, a family accepted by most linguists, with Robert M.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] For convenience, the rest of the languages, all spoken in the far north, are commonly lumped together as "Non-Pama–Nyungan", although this does not necessarily imply that they constitute a valid clade.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Dixon argues that after perhaps 40,000 years of mutual influence and only a few centuries of written records, it is no longer possible to distinguish deep genealogical relationships from areal features in Australia, and that not even Pama–Nyungan is a valid language family.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] However, few other linguists accept Dixon's thesis.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Hale describes Dixon's scepticism as an erroneous phylogenetic assessment which is "such an insult to the eminently successful practitioners of Comparative Method Linguistics in Australia, that it positively demands a decisive riposte".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Johanna Nichols suggests that the northern families may be relatively recent arrivals from Maritime Southeast Asia, perhaps later replaced there by the spread of Austronesian.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] That could explain the typological difference between Pama–Nyungan and non-Pama–Nyungan languages, but not how a single family came to be so widespread.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Nicholas Evans suggests that the Pama–Nyungan family spread along with the now-dominant Aboriginal culture that includes the Australian Aboriginal kinship system.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] This Proto-Australian language, they concluded, would have been spoken about 12,000 years ago in northern Australia.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2024, Harvey and Mailhammer published a book-length reconstruction of Proto-Australian.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] For a long time unsuccessful attempts were made to detect a link between Australian and Papuan languages, the latter being represented by those spoken on the coastal areas of New Guinea facing the Torres Strait and the Arafura Sea.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Foley noted lexical similarities between Robert M.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Dixon's 1980 reconstruction of proto-Australian and the East New Guinea Highlands languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Dixon, in the meantime, later abandoned his proto-Australian proposal.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] According to Claire Bowern's *Australian Languages* (2011), Australian languages divide into approximately 30 primary sub-groups and 5 isolates.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 1962, Arthur Capell gave his assessment of the origins and internal grouping of Aboriginal languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] He referred to many attempts having been made to link the Australian languages to other parts of the world, including the Dravidian languages of South India, those of the Andaman Islands, and African languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Unclassified groups occupying the bulk of Queensland and New South Wales.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 1967 Carl Georg von Brandenstein claimed that he had isolated and identified some sixty Portuguese language loanwords in several indigenous languages of Australia's far north.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Australian linguists have generally dismissed these conclusions, except perhaps for the word *tartaruga*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Nick Thieberger, a Melbourne University linguist, argues that Brandenstein's approach was still strongly influenced by outdated nineteenth-century linguistic thinking.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] It has been inferred from the probable number of languages and the estimate of pre-contact population levels that there may have been from 3,000 to 4,000 speakers on average for each of the 250 languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] A number of these languages were almost immediately wiped out within decades of colonisation, the case of the Aboriginal Tasmanians being a notorious example.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Tasmania had been separated from the mainland at the end of the Quaternary glaciation, and Indigenous Tasmanians remained isolated from the outside world for around 12,000 years.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Claire Bowern has concluded in a recent study that there were twelve Tasmanian languages, and that those languages are unrelated (that is, not demonstrably related) to those on the Australian mainland.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 1990 it was estimated that 90 languages still survived of the approximately 250 once spoken, but with a high rate of attrition as elders died out.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Of the 90, 70% by 2001 were judged as 'severely endangered' with only 17 spoken by all age groups, a definition of a 'strong' language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] On these grounds it is anticipated that despite efforts at linguistic preservation, many of the remaining languages will disappear within the next generation.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The overall trend suggests that in the not too distant future all of the Indigenous languages will be lost, perhaps by 2050, and with them the cultural knowledge they convey.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] During the period of the Stolen Generations, Aboriginal children were removed from their families and placed in institutions where they were punished for speaking their Indigenous language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Different, mutually unintelligible language groups were often mixed together, with Australian Aboriginal English or Australian Kriol language as the only lingua franca.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The result was a disruption to the inter-generational transmission of these languages that severely impacted their future use.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Today, that same transmission of language between parents and grandparents to their children is a key mechanism for reversing language shift.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] There is some evidence to suggest that the reversal of the Indigenous language shift may lead to decreased self-harm and suicide rates among Indigenous youth.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Nya jawgar yaam Gumbayynggir.*" (Translation: My father is Dhunghutti.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] And, therefore, I am Gumbayynggir.) In the House of Representatives on 31 August 2016 Linda Burney gave an acknowledgment of country in Wiradjuri in her first speech and was sung in by Lynette Riley in Wiradjuri from the public gallery.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] 2019 was the International Year of Indigenous Languages (IYIL2019), as declared by the United Nations General Assembly.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The commemoration was used to raise awareness of and support for the preservation of Aboriginal languages within Australia, including spreading knowledge about the importance of each language to the identity and knowledge of Indigenous groups.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Warrgamay/Girramay man Troy Wyles-Whelan joined the North Queensland Regional Aboriginal Corporation Language Centre (NQRACLC) in 2008, and has been contributing oral histories and the results of his own research to their database.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] As part of the efforts to raise awareness of the Wiradjuri language, a *Grammar of Wiradjuri language* was published in 2014 and *A new Wiradjuri dictionary* in 2010.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The New South Wales *Aboriginal Languages Act 2017* became law on 24 October 2017 and established a board to advise on the preservation of Aboriginal languages that is known as the Aboriginal Languages Trust.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] It was the first legislation in Australia to acknowledge the significance of first languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2019 the Royal Australian Mint issued a 50-cent coin to celebrate the International Year of Indigenous Languages which features 14 different words for "money" from Australian Indigenous languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The coin was designed by Aleksandra Stokic in consultation with Indigenous language custodian groups.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The work of digitising and transcribing many word lists created by ethnographer Daisy Bates in the 1900s at Daisy Bates Online provides a valuable resource for those researching especially Western Australian languages, and some languages of the Northern Territory and South Australia.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The project is co-ordinated by Nick Thieberger, who works in collaboration with the National Library of Australia "to have all the microfilmed images from Section XII of the Bates papers digitised".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The project is succeeded by the Nyingarn Project , which digitises manuscripts and crowdsources transcriptions through DigiVol.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In recent decades, there have been attempts to revive indigenous languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Significant challenges exist, however, for the revival of languages in the dominant English language culture of Australia.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The Kaurna language, spoken by the Kaurna people of the Adelaide plains, has been the subject of a concerted revival movement since the 1980s, coordinated by Kaurna Warra Pintyanthi, a unit working out of the University of Adelaide.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The language had rapidly disappeared after the settlement of South Australia and the breaking up of local indigenous people.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Ivaritji, the last known speaker of the language, died in 1931.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] However, a substantial number of primary source records existed for the language, from which the language was reconstructed.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The Tasmanian Aboriginal Centre, in collaboration with the University of Tasmania and the wider Aboriginal community, is undergoing the process of reviving Traditional Tasmanian languages through the construction of *palawa kani* (trans.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The *palawa kani* Language Program has been in the works since the early 1990s.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Due to the linguistic ethnocide of Aboriginal Tasmanians, *palawa kani* is the only Aboriginal language of Lutruwita/Tasmania today.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] "Some Aboriginal people distinguish between *usership* and *ownership*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Whether it is due to genetic unity or some other factor such as occasional contact, typologically the Australian languages form a language area or *Sprachbund*, sharing much of their vocabulary and many distinctive phonological features across the entire continent.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] A common feature of many Australian languages is that they display so-called avoidance speech, special speech registers used only in the presence of certain close relatives.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] These registers share the phonology and grammar of the standard language, but the lexicon is different and usually very restricted.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] There are also commonly speech taboos during extended periods of mourning or initiation that have led to numerous Aboriginal sign languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] For morphosyntactic alignment, many Australian languages have ergative–absolutive case systems.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] These are typically split systems; a widespread pattern is for pronouns (or first and second persons) to have nominative–accusative case marking and for third person to be ergative–absolutive, though splits between animate and inanimate are also found.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In some languages the persons in between the accusative and ergative inflections (such as second person, or third-person human) may be tripartite: that is, marked overtly as either ergative or accusative in transitive clauses, but not marked as either in intransitive clauses.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] There are also a few languages which employ only nominative–accusative case marking.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The following represents a canonical 6-place Australian Aboriginal consonant system.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] It does not represent any single language, but is instead a simplified form of the consonant inventory of what would be found in many Australian languages, including most Arandic and Yolŋu languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] A typical Australian phonological inventory includes just three vowels, usually /i, u, a/, which may occur in both long and short variants.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In a few cases the [u] has been unrounded to give [i, ɯ, a].
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] There is almost never a voicing contrast; that is, a consonant may sound like a [p] at the beginning of a word, but like a [b] between vowels, and either letter could be (and often is) chosen to represent it.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Australia also stands out as being almost entirely free of fricative consonants, even of the otherwise universal [s].
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In the few cases where fricatives do occur, they developed recently through the lenition (weakening) of stops, and are therefore non-sibilants like [ð] rather than the sibilants like [s] that are common elsewhere in the world.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some languages also have three rhotics, typically a flap, a trill, and an approximant (that is, like the combined rhotics of English and Spanish) and many have four laterals.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Besides the lack of fricatives, the most striking feature of Australian speech sounds is the large number of places of articulation.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some 10-15% of Australian languages have four places of articulation, with two coronal places of articulation, 40-50% have five places, and 40-45% have six places of articulation, including four coronals.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The four-way distinction in the coronal region is commonly accomplished through two variables: the position of the tongue (front, alveolar or dental, or retroflex), and its shape (apical or laminal).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] There are also bilabial, velar and often palatal consonants, but a complete absence of uvular consonants and only a few languages with a glottal stop.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Both stops and nasals occur at all six places, and in many languages laterals occur at all four coronal places.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] A language which displays the full range of stops, nasals and laterals is Kalkatungu, which has labial *p, m*; "dental" *th, nh, lh*; "alveolar" *t, n, l*; "retroflex" *rt, rn, rl*; "palatal" *ty, ny, ly*; and velar *k, ng*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Wangganguru has all this, as well as three rhotics.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Yanyuwa has even more contrasts, with an additional true dorso-palatal series, plus prenasalised consonants at all *seven* places of articulation, in addition to all four laterals.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Where vowels are concerned, it has 8 vowels with some morpho-syntactic as well as phonemic length contrasts (i iː, e eː, a aː, ə əː, ɔ ɔː, o oː, ʊ ʊː, u uː), and glides that distinguish between those that are in origin vowels, and those that in origin are consonants.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Kunjen and other neighbouring languages have also developed contrasting aspirated consonants ([pʰ], [t̪ʰ], [tʰ], [cʰ], [kʰ]) not found further south.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Descriptions of the coronal articulations can be inconsistent.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The alveolar series *t, n, l* (or *d, n, l*) is straightforward: across the continent, these sounds are alveolar (that is, pronounced by touching the tongue to the ridge just behind the gum line of the upper teeth) and apical (that is, touching that ridge with the tip of the tongue).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] This is very similar to English *t, d, n, l*, though the Australian *t* is not aspirated, even in Kalaw Lagaw Ya, despite its other stops being aspirated.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The other apical series is the retroflex, *rt, rn, rl* (or *rd, rn, rl*).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Here the place is further back in the mouth, in the postalveolar or prepalatal region.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The articulation is actually most commonly subapical; that is, the tongue curls back so that the *underside* of the tip makes contact.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] That is, they are true retroflex consonants.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] It has been suggested that subapical pronunciation is characteristic of more careful speech, while these sounds tend to be apical in rapid speech.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Kalaw Lagaw Ya and many other languages in North Queensland differ from most other Australian languages in not having a retroflexive series.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The first tends to be used in careful enunciation, and the last in more rapid speech, while the tongue-down articulation is less common.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Finally, the palatal series *ty, ny, ly*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] (The stop is often spelled *dj*, *tj*, or *j*.) Here the contact is also laminal, but further back, spanning the alveolar to postalveolar, or the postalveolar to prepalatal regions.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The tip of the tongue is typically down behind the lower teeth.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] This is similar to the "closed" articulation of Circassian fricatives (see Postalveolar consonant).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The body of the tongue is raised towards the palate.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] This is similar to the "domed" English postalveolar fricative *sh*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Because the tongue is "peeled" from the roof of the mouth from back to front during the release of these stops, there is a fair amount of frication, giving the *ty* something of the impression of the English palato-alveolar affricate *ch* or the Polish alveolo-palatal affricate *ć*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] That is, these consonants are not palatal in the IPA sense of the term, and indeed they contrast with true palatals in Yanyuwa.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In Kalaw Lagaw Ya, the palatal consonants are sub-phonemes of the alveolar sibilants /s/ and /z/.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] These descriptions do not apply exactly to all Australian languages, as the notes regarding Kalaw Lagaw Ya demonstrate.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] However, they do describe most of them, and are the expected norm against which languages are compared.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some have suggested that the most appropriate unit to describe the phonotactics of Australian languages is the phonological word.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The optionality of CFIN is cross-linguistically normal, since coda consonants are weak or nonexistent in many languages, as well as in the early stages of language acquisition.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The weakening of CINIT, on the other hand, is very unusual.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] No Australian language has consonant clusters in this position, and those languages with fortis and lenis distinctions do not make such distinctions in this position.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Place of articulation distinctions are also less common in this position, and lenitions and deletions are historically common here.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] While in most languages the word-initial position is prominent, maintaining all a language's contrasts, that is not the case in Australia.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Here the prominent position is C1(C2), in the middle of the word.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] C1 is typically the only position allowing all of a language's place of articulation contrasts.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Fortis/lenis contrasts can only occur at C1, or at C2 when C1 is a sonorant.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Consonant clusters are often restricted to the C1(C2) position, and are most commonly sonorant + obstruent sequences.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In languages with pre-stopped nasals or laterals, those sounds only occur at C1.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Australian languages typically resist certain connected speech processes which might blur the place of articulation of consonants at C1(C2), such as anticipatory assimilation of place of articulation, which is common around the world.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In Australia, this type of assimilation seems only to have affected consonants within the apical and laminal categories.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] There's little evidence of assimilation between the labial, apical, laminal, and dorsal categories.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Many proto-Pama–Nyungan /-np-/ and /-nk-/ clusters have been preserved across Australia.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Heterorganic nasal + stop sequences remain stable even in modern connected speech, which is highly unusual.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The anticipatory assimilation of nasality is quite common in various languages around the world.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Typically, a vowel will become nasalized before a following nasal consonant.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] However, this process is resisted in Australian languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] There was a historical process in many languages where nasal + stop C1C2 clusters lost the nasal element if CINIT was a nasal.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Also, many languages have morphophonemic alterations whereby initial nasals in suffixes are denasalized if the preceding stem contains a nasal consonant.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] While the existence of phonemic pre-stopped nasals and laterals, contrasting with plain nasals and laterals, has been documented in some Australian languages, nasals and laterals are pre-stopped on a phonetic level in most languages of the continent.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] These phenomena are the result of a general resistance to the anticipatory assimilation of nasality and laterality.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] The lack of assimilation makes coda nasals and laterals more acoustically distinct.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Most speakers of Australian languages speak with a 'pressed' voice quality, with the glottal opening narrower than in modal voice, a relatively high frequency of creaky voice, and low airflow.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] This may be due to an avoidance of breathy voice.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] This pressed quality could therefore serve to enhance the clarity of speech and ensure the perception of place of articulation distinctions.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Probably every Australian language with speakers remaining has had an orthography developed for it, in each case in the Latin script.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Sounds not found in English are usually represented by digraphs, or more rarely by diacritics, such as underlines, or extra symbols, sometimes borrowed from the International Phonetic Alphabet.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some examples are shown in the following table.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In the Northern Territory, 62.5% of Aboriginal Australians spoke an indigenous language at home in 2016.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] In Queensland, almost 95% of Torres Strait Islanders spoke an indigenous language at home in 2016.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aboriginal-australian-languages] A number of linguists and ethnographers have contributed greatly to the sum of knowledge about Australian languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adithinngithigh-language] However, it is not clear how distinct the two varieties are.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] The **Adnyamathanha language** (pronounced /ˈɑːdnjəmʌdənə/), also known as **yura ngarwala** natively and **Kuyani**, also known as **Guyani** and other variants, are two closely related Australian Aboriginal languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] They are traditional languages of the Adnyamathanha of and the Kuyani peoples, of the Flinders Ranges and to the west of the Flinders respectively, in South Australia.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] As of the 2021 Australian census, there were around 262 speakers of Adnyamathanha, up from 140 in 2016, making it an endangered language; there have been no speakers of Kuyani recorded since 1975.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] The first bilingual dictionary of the language was published in November 2020.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] The name of the witchetty grub comes from Adnyamathanha.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Guyani is also spelled *Kijani, Kuyani, Kwiani*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Dixon classifies Adnyamathanha and Guyani as a single language, Ethnologue, Glottolog and AIATSIS treats them as separate languages, L10: Adnyamathanha and L9: Kuyani.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Estimates of the number of people who speak Adnyamathanha are variable, though it is a severely endangered language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] According to Oates (1973) there were only 30 speakers, around 20 according to Schmidt in 1990, 127 in the 1996 Australian census, 140 in the 2016 census and 262 in 2021.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Adjnjamathanha and Guyani have the same phonemic inventory.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Most of the nasals and laterals are allophonically prestopped.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] While the closely related Guyani retains word-initial stops, Adnyamathanha has undergone systematic lenition of stops in this position.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Former *p has become [v], former *t̪ and probably also *c have become /j/, and former *k has disappeared entirely.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Adnyamathanha has a complex system of personal pronouns.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] There are 10 different ways of saying we "you and I" (first person dual), depending on the relationship between the speaker and the addressee.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] The linguist Bernhard Schebeck travelled to the Nepabunna region in the 1970s, and wrote *An Adnyamathanha-English Research Dictionary* in 2000, which was "For private, or internal, use only – not for publication".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Dorothy Tunbridge, a linguist from Canberra and author of *Flinders Ranges Dreaming* visited the area in the 1980s.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Both contributed much to knowledge of the language, but neither recorded all of the words that were known to local speakers.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] In November 2020 the first-ever bilingual Adnyamathanha/English dictionary and grammar was published, with translations from and to each language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Compiled by Terrence Coulthard and his wife Josephine, the 400-page *Adnyamathanha Culture Guide and Language Book* includes descriptions of cultural practices, songlines (*muda*), the Adnyamathanha kinship system and social history.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Terrence, an Adnyamathanha speaker, had been collecting information on the culture and language for 40 years, building on the earlier work by Schebeck and Tunbridge.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Linguists and others from the University of Adelaide's Mobile Language Team helped the couple to finalise work on the book in the 18 months to two years before publication.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] The Coulthards run Iga Warta, a cultural tourism enterprise, located near Nepabunna in the Gammon Ranges, the site of a mission where Terrence grew up.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/adnyamathanha-language] Iga Warta means "native orange", named by 19th-century English botanist John Lindley as *Capparis mitchelii*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In linguistics, **agglutination** is a morphological process in which words are formed by stringing together morphemes (word parts), each of which corresponds to a single syntactic feature.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Languages that use agglutination widely are called agglutinative languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, in the agglutinative Turkish, the word *evlerinizden* ("from your houses") consists of the morphemes *ev-ler-i-n-iz-den*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Agglutinative languages are often contrasted with isolating languages, in which words are monomorphemic, and fusional languages, in which words can be complex, but morphemes may correspond to multiple features.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Although agglutination is characteristic of certain language families, this does not mean that when several languages in a certain geographic area are all agglutinative they are necessarily related phylogenetically.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In the past, this assumption led linguists to propose the so-called Ural–Altaic language family, which included the Uralic and Turkic languages, as well as Mongolian, Korean, and Japanese.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Contemporary linguistics views this proposal as controversial, and some refer to this as a language convergence instead.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Another consideration when evaluating the above proposal is that some languages that developed from agglutinative proto-languages lost their agglutinative features.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, contemporary Estonian has shifted towards the fusional type.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Examples of agglutinative languages include the Uralic languages, such as Finnish, Estonian, and Hungarian.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] These have highly agglutinated expressions in daily usage, and most words are bisyllabic or longer.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Grammatical information expressed by adpositions in Western Indo-European languages is typically found in suffixes.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Hungarian uses extensive agglutination in almost every part of it.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The suffixes follow each other in special order based on the role of the suffix, and many can be heaped, one upon the other, resulting in words conveying complex meanings in compacted forms.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] An example is *fiaiéi*, where the root "fi(ú)-" means "son", the subsequent four vowels are all separate suffixes, and the whole word means "[plural properties] belong to his/her sons".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The nested possessive structure and expression of plurals are quite remarkable (note that Hungarian uses no genders).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Though Indo-European languages are generally non-agglutinating, there are exceptions.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Persian has some features of agglutination, making use of prefixes and suffixes attached to the stems of verbs and nouns.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Persian is an SOV language, thus having a head-final phrase structure.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Persian utilizes a noun root + plural suffix + case suffix + postposition suffix syntax similar to Turkish.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, the phrase "*Mashinhayeshan-ra negah mikardam*/ماشین‌های‌شان را نگاه می‌کردم" meaning 'I was looking at their cars' lit.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Breaking down the first word: ماشین(car)+(ها(ی(plural suffix)+شان(possessive suffix)+را(post-positional suffix) We can see its agglutinative nature and the fact that Persian is able to affix a given number of dependent morphemes to a root morpheme (in this example, car).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Almost all Austronesian languages, such as Malay, and most Philippine languages, also belong to this category, thus enabling them to form new words from simple base forms.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The Indonesian and Malay word *mempertanggungjawabkan* is formed by adding active-voice, causative and benefactive affixes to the compound verb *tanggung jawab*, which means "to account for".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In Tagalog (and its standardised register, Filipino), *nakakapágpabagabag* ("that which is upsetting/disturbing") is formed from the root *bagabag* ("upsetting" or "disquieting").
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In East Asia, Korean is an agglutinating language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Its uses of '조사', '접사', and '어미' makes Korean agglutinate.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] They represent tense, time, number, causality, and honorific forms.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Japanese is also an agglutinating language, like Korean, adding information such as negation, passive voice, past tense, honorific degree and causality in the verb form.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The "-siniz" refers to plural form of you with "-sin" being the singular form, the same way "-im" being "I" ("-im" means "my" not "I".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The original editor must have mistaken it for "-yim".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] This second suffix is used as such "Oraya gideyim" meaning "May I go there" or "When I get there") and "-imiz" making it become "we".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Similarly, this suffix means "our" and not "we".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In all Dravidian languages, verbal markers are used to convey tense and mood, and usually person (though Malayalam is an exception to the latter).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, in Tamil, "சாப்பிடுகிறேன்" (*cāppiṭukiṟēṉ*, "I eat") is formed from the verb root சாப்பிடு- (*cāppiṭu-*, "to eat") + the present tense marker -கிற்- (*-kiṟ-*) + the first-person singular suffix -ஏன் (*-ēṉ*).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Agglutination is also a notable feature of Basque.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Another example would be the declension: *Etxean* = "In the house" where *etxe* = house.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Agglutination is used very heavily in most Native American languages, such as the Inuit languages, Nahuatl, Mapudungun, Quechua, Tz'utujil, Kaqchikel, Cha'palaachi and Kʼicheʼ, where one word can contain enough morphemes to convey the meaning of what would be a complex sentence in other languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Conversely, Navajo contains affixes for some uses, but overlays them in such unpredictable and inseparable ways that it is often referred to as a fusional language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] As noted above, it is a typical feature of agglutinative languages that there is a one-to-one correspondence between suffixes and syntactic categories.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, a noun may have separate markers for number, case, possessive or conjunctive usage etc.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The order of these affixes is fixed, so we may view any given noun or verb as a stem followed by several inflectional and derivational "slots", i.e. positions in which particular suffixes may occur, and/or preceded by several "slots" for prefixes.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] It is often the case that the most common instance of a given grammatical category is unmarked, i.e. the corresponding affix is empty.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The number of slots for a given part of speech can be surprisingly high.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] 2. tense: *-(e)ss* (었) for completed (past) action or state; when this slot is empty, the tense is interpreted as present (The 'ss' is pronounced as 't' if it is placed behind a consonant.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, -었어(ess-e) is pronounced as (esse), but -었다(ess-ta) is pronounced as (etta).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Moreover, passive and causative verbal forms can be derived by adding suffixes to the base, which could be seen as the null-th slot.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Even though some combinations of suffixes are not possible (e.g. only one of the aspect slots may be filled with a non-empty suffix), over 400 verb forms may be formed from a single base.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Although most agglutinative languages in Europe and Asia are predominantly suffixing, the Bantu languages of eastern and southern Africa are known for a highly complex mixture of prefixes, suffixes and reduplication.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] A typical feature of this language family is that nouns fall into noun classes.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For each noun class, there are specific singular and plural prefixes, which also serve as markers of agreement between the subject and the verb.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Moreover, the noun determines prefixes of all words that modify it and subject determines prefixes of other elements in the same verb phrase.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, the Swahili nouns *-toto* ("child") and *-tu* ("person") fall into class 1, with singular prefix *m-* and plural prefix *wa-*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The noun *-tabu* ("book") falls into class 7, with singular prefix *ki-* and plural prefix *vi-*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The American linguist Joseph Harold Greenberg in his 1960 paper proposed to use the so-called *agglutinative index* to calculate a numerical value that would allow a researcher to compare the "degree of agglutitativeness" of various languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For Greenberg, *agglutination* means that the morphs are joined only with slight or no modification.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] A morpheme is said to be automatic if it either takes a single surface form (morph), or if its surface form is determined by phonological rules that hold in all similar instances in that language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] A morph juncture—a position in a word where two morphs meet—is considered agglutinative when both morphemes included are automatic.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The index of agglutination is equal to the average ratio of the number of agglutinative junctures to the number of morph junctures.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Languages with high values of the agglutinative index are agglutinative and with low values of the agglutinative index are fusional.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In the same paper, Greenberg proposed several other indices, many of which turn out to be relevant to the study of agglutination.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The *synthetic index* is the average number of morphemes per word, with the lowest conceivable value equal to 1 for isolating (analytic) languages and real-life values rarely exceeding 3.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The compounding index is equal to the average number of root morphemes per word (as opposed to derivational and inflectional morphemes).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The derivational, inflectional, prefixial and suffixial indices correspond respectively to the average number of derivational and inflectional morphemes, prefixes and suffixes.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The one-to-one relationship between an affix and its grammatical function may be somewhat complicated by the phonological processes active in the given language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Several examples from Finnish will illustrate how these two rules and other phonological processes lead to diversions from the basic one-to-one relationship between morphs and their syntactic and semantic function.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] No phonological rule is applied in the declension of *talo* 'house'.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] However, the second example illustrates several kinds of phonological phenomena.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] It is possible to construct artificially extreme examples of agglutination, which have no real use, but illustrate the theoretical capability of the grammar to agglutinate.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] This is not a question of "long words", because some languages permit limitless combinations with compound words, negative clitics or such, which can be (and are) expressed with an analytic structure in actual usage.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] English is capable of agglutinating morphemes of solely native (Germanic) origin, as *un-whole-some-ness*, but generally speaking the longest words are assembled from forms of Latin or Ancient Greek origin.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The classic example is *antidisestablishmentarianism*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Agglutinative languages often have more complex derivational agglutination than isolating languages, so they can do the same to a much larger extent.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, in Hungarian, a word such as *elnemzetietleníthetetlenségnek*, which means "for [the purposes of] undenationalizationability" can find actual use.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In the same way, there are the words that have meaning, but probably are never used such as *legeslegmegszentségteleníttethetetlenebbjeitekként*, which means "like the most of most undesecratable ones of you", but is hard to decipher even for native speakers.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Using inflectional agglutination, these can be extended.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, the official Guinness world record is Finnish *epäjärjestelmällistyttämättömyydellänsäkäänköhän* "I wonder if – even with his/her quality of not having been made unsystematized".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] It has the derived word *epäjärjestelmällistyttämättömyys* as the root and is lengthened with the inflectional endings ‑*llänsäkäänköhän*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] However, this word is grammatically unusual, because *-kään* "also" is used only in negative clauses, but *-kö* (question) only in question clauses.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] A very popular Turkish agglutination is *Çekoslovakyalılaştıramadıklarımızdanmışsınız*, meaning "(Apparently / I've heard that) You are one of those that we were not able to convert into Czechoslovaks".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] This historical reference is used as a joke for the individuals who are hard to change or those who stick out in a group.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] On the other hand, *Afyonkarahisarlılaştırabildiklerimizdenmişsinizcesine* is a longer word that does not surprise people and means "As if you were one of those we were able to make resemble people from Afyonkarahisar".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Georgian is also a highly agglutinative language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] For example, the word *gadmosakontrrevolucieleblebisnairebisatvisaco* (გადმოსაკონტრრევოლუციელებლებისნაირებისათვისაცო) would mean "(someone not specified) said that it is also for those who are like the ones who need to be to again/back counter-revolutionized".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] It was created to ridicule a trend for long compounds in Attic Greek at the time.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Slavic languages are not considered agglutinative but fusional.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] However, extreme derivations similar to ones found in typical agglutinative languages do exist.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] A famous example is the Bulgarian word *непротивоконституциослователствувайте*, meaning *don't speak against the constitution* and secondarily *don't act against the constitution*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] It is composed of just three roots: против *against*, конституция *constitution*, a loan word and therefore devoid of its internal composition and слово *word*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The remaining are bound morphemes for negation (*не*, a proclitic, otherwise written separately in verbs), noun intensifier (*-ателств*), noun-to-verb conversion (*-ува*), imperative mood second person plural ending (*-йте*).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] It is rather unusual, but finds some usage, e.g. newspaper headlines on 13 July 1991, the day after the current Bulgarian constitution was adopted with much controversy and debate, and even scandals.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The words *agglutination* and *agglutinative* come from the Latin word *agglutinare*, 'to glue together'.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In linguistics, these words have been in use since 1836, when Wilhelm von Humboldt's posthumously published work *Über die Verschiedenheit des menschlichen Sprachbaues und ihren Einfluß auf die geistige Entwicklung des Menschengeschlechts* lit.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] 'On the differences of human language construction and its influence on the mental development of mankind' introduced the division of languages into *isolating*, *inflectional*, *agglutinative* and *incorporating*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Especially in some older literature, *agglutinative* is sometimes used as a synonym for *synthetic*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In that case, it embraces what we call agglutinative and inflectional languages, and it is an antonym of *analytic* or *isolating*.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Besides the clear etymological motivation (after all, inflectional endings are also "glued" to the stems), this more general usage is justified by the fact that the distinction between agglutinative and inflectional languages is not a sharp one, as we have already seen.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The following passage from Lord (1960) demonstrates well the whole range of meanings that the word *agglutination* may have.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In natural language processing, languages with rich morphology pose problems of quite a different kind than isolating languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In the case of agglutinative languages, the main obstacle lies in the large number of word forms that can be obtained from a single root.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] As we have already seen, the generation of these word forms is somewhat complicated by the phonological processes of the particular language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Although the basic one-to-one relationship between form and syntactic function is not broken in Finnish, the authoritative institution Institute for the Languages of Finland (*Kotus*) lists 51 declension types for Finnish nouns, adjectives, pronouns, and numerals.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Even more problems occur with the recognition of word forms.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Modern linguistic methods are largely based on the exploitation of corpora; however, when the number of possible word forms is large, any corpus will necessarily contain only a small fraction of them.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Hajič (2010) claims that computer space and power are so cheap nowadays that all possible word forms may be generated beforehand and stored in a form of a lexicon listing all possible interpretations of any given word form.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] (The data structure of the lexicon has to be optimized so that the search is quick and efficient.) According to Hajič, it is the disambiguation of these word forms which is difficult (more so for inflective languages where the ambiguity is high than for agglutinative languages).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] Other authors do not share Hajič's view that space is no issue and instead of listing all possible word forms in a lexicon, word form analysis is implemented by modules which try to break up the surface form into a sequence of morphemes occurring in an order permissible by the language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] The problem of such an analysis is the large number of morpheme boundaries typical for agglutinative languages.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] A word of an inflectional language has only one ending and therefore the number of possible divisions of a word into the base and the ending is only linear with the length of the word.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] In an agglutinative language, where several suffixes are concatenated at the end of the word, the number of different divisions which have to be checked for consistency is large.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/agglutination] This approach was used for example in the development of a system for Arabic, where agglutination occurs when articles, prepositions and conjunctions are joined with the following word and pronouns are joined with the preceding word.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aghu-tharrnggala-language] Aghu Tharrnggala is demonstrably related to Kuku-Thaypan and Rarmul.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aghu-tharrnggala-language] The two may also have been related to Takalak, although there is insufficient information for this to be certain.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aghu-tharrnggala-language] The consonant phonemes of Aghu Tharrnggala are located in the chart below.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/alawa-language] Alawa has a typical consonant inventory for an Indigenous Australian language, with five contrastive places of articulation, multiple lateral consonants, and no voicing contrast among the stops.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/alawa-language] Note: there are no standardised IPA symbols for alveopalatal stops.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/alawa-language] The vowel system of Alawa is made up of four vowel phonemes: the high front vowel /i/, the high back vowel /u/, the mid front vowel /e/, and the low central vowel /a/.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/alawa-language] There are no rounding contrasts or length contrasts in this language.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The local Anindilyakwa people refer to the language as Amamalya Ayakwa (*Amamalya* means 'true' and *Ayakwa* means 'words').
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] However, Anindilyakwa is still commonly used.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Before a standard orthography was established, the name **Anindilyakwa** had been spelt in multiple ways.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] These included **Andiljangwa**, **Andilyaugwa**, **Aninhdhilyagwa**, **Enindiljaugwa**, **Enindhilyagwa**, **Wanindilyaugwaz.** The language was also known as **Ingura**, **Yingguru,** and **Groote Eylandt** after its location.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The analysis of Anindilyakwa's vowels is open to interpretation.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Stokes analyses it as having 4 phonemic vowels, /i e a u/.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Leeding analyses it as having just 2, /ɨ a/ with allophones [ i ɪ u ɯ ə o a ] and [ a æ aɪ æɪ e eɪ ɒ aʊ ], respectively.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Anindilyakwa words almost always end with a final vowel 'a'.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Clusters of up to 3 consonants such as 'ngw' can occur within words.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] For bound pronouns, instead of "human male" and "non-human male" classes there is a single "male" class.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] All traditional Anindilyakwa nouns carry a class prefix, but some loanwords may lack them.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The language traditionally had numerals up to 20 but since the introduction of English, English words are now used almost exclusively for numbers above 5.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Anindilyakwa uses a quinary (base-5) number system, where numbers act like adjectives and must agree with the noun class of the word they describe.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] For example, 'one crocodile' is *dawilyaba dingarrbiya*, and 'two turtles' is *yambilyuma yimenda*, with the number prefix matching the noun class of the noun.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] 'Nothing' is expressed by *nara ebina*, 'not any'.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Size degrees is done in 2 grades the positive and a diminutive (*warrngka*), although reduplication of this word is possible for an intensifying effect.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Anindilyakwa features 5 grammatical numbers for pronouns: singular, feminine dual, masculine dual, trial, and plural.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The language has a clusivity distinction common in many Aboriginal Australian languages – *ngakwurruwa* 'inclusive we' and *yirruwa* 'exclusive we'.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] 'Inclusive we' includes explicitly the addressee (that is, 'you and I, and possibly others').
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] 'Exclusive we' excludes explicitly the addressee (that is, 'he/she/they and I, but not you'), regardless of who else may be involved.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] With the exception of *my*, possessive pronouns in Anindilyakwa replace the *-uwa* suffix from the singular or plural pronouns with *-langwa* 'belonging to'.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] For kinship nouns, there are 7 possessive suffixes used that distinguish between first, second and thirds, singular or plural numbers, and third person genders.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The Groote Eylandt Language Centre (GELC) promotes, maintains, and preserves Anindilyakwa.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] They are based in Angurugu with offices in Umbakumba and Bickerton Island.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] It hosts a significant collection of language and cultural resources relating to the Warnindilyakwa people.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The Centre undertakes language projects both large and small and offers services such as language recording and resource development, language advice and expertise, and translation.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Previously known as Groote Eylandt Linguistics, Church Mission Society ran the department until 2006.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The CMS created the orthography with the Latin script to translate Bible texts into Anindilyakwa.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The centre now operates under the "Preserving Culture" department of the Anindilyakwa Land Council.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] GELC has compiled and published the Anindilyakwa dictionary *Eningerriberra-langwa jurra* "The Book about Everything", as well as producing an online dictionary, and a web app with the assistance of the Australian Literacy and Numeracy Foundation.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] They also run a YouTube channel with an expanding content of videos and resources in Anindilyakwa.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Makassar people from the region of Sulawesi (modern-day Indonesia) began visiting the coast of northern Australia sometime around the early to middle 1700s.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] This happened yearly until the introduction of the White Australia Policy in 1906.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The Macassans visited Groote Eylandt for trade, particularly for highly prized trepang in the South China Sea.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] The Macassans also brought with them tamarinds (*jamba*), dugout canoes (*malamukwa*), tobacco (*dambakwa*) and beer (*anija*).
[src:anindilyakwa-language/anindilyakwa-language] Evan analyses that there are potentially 35 Makassarese words, mostly nouns, that have entered the Anindilyakwa language, including many place names such as Umbakumba (Malay word *ombak-ombak* for 'lapping of waves') and Bartalumba Bay (Macassan word *batu lompoa* for 'the big rock').
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] It oversees the collection, administration and distribution of music licences and royalties.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The association has more than 190 members, including small labels typically run by one to five people, medium-size organisations and very large companies with international affiliates.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] ARIA is administered by a board of directors comprising senior executives from record companies, both large and small.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] In 1956, the Association of Australian Record Manufacturers (AARM) was formed by Australia's major record companies.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] It later included smaller record companies representing independent acts/labels and has over 100 members.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] By 1997, the six major labels provided 90% of all recordings made in Australia.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The **ARIA Charts** is the main Australian music sales charts, issued weekly by the Australian Recording Industry Association.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The charts are a record of the highest selling singles and albums in various genres.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] All charts are compiled from data of both physical and digital sales from retailers in Australia.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The first printed national top 50 chart available in record stores, branded the *Countdown* chart, was dated the week ending 10 July 1983.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] ARIA began compiling its own charts in-house from the chart survey dated 13 June 1988, corresponding with the printed top 50 chart dated the week ending 26 June 1988, at which time it became the official Australian chart.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] A music single or album qualifies for a platinum certification if it exceeds 70,000 copies shipped to retailers and a gold certification for 35,000 copies shipped.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The diamond certification was created in November 2015 to mark 500,000 sales/shipments.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The diamond award includes an aggregation of sales of albums plus the sales of the tracks from that album after 1 July 2014, where 10 track sales equal one album.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] A silver certification for albums was introduced in November 2024.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The silver award applies only to albums by Australian artists, released no earlier than 2021 and the required level of 20,000 units must be achieved within three years of the album's release.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] For music DVDs (formerly videos), a gold accreditation originally represented 7,500 copies shipped, with a platinum accreditation representing 15,000 units shipped.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Single figures can include "qualifying streams" since July 2015.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Since March 2022 this also includes Official Content streams on YouTube.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] On 1 January 1977, the Australian Record Industry Association announced major revisions in its accreditation awards system.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] No longer were awards based on dollar terms but, rather, unit sales.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Gold records will be awarded to singles selling 50,000 units, EPs selling 30,000 units and albums selling 20,000 units.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] At the same time, the industry introduced a platinum award in recognition of the growth achievement of the Australian market.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Platinum awards were issued to singles selling 100,000 and albums selling 50,000 units.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Prior to 1977, awards were based on dollar value rather than unit sales and only issued gold awards.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] 1 Chart Awards** were established in 2002 to recognise Australian recording artists, who reached number one on the ARIA albums, singles and music DVDs charts.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Since May 2014, international artists have also been eligible to receive the award.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The awarding process is retroactive, meaning that records which peaked at number one prior to the introduction of the awards are still eligible to receive the award.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] A similar **Australian Chart #1 Awards** was established in August 2024, awarded to artists topping the Australian Albums Chart and Australian Singles Chart.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The **ARIA Music Awards** is an annual series of awards nights celebrating the Australian music industry.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Australian TV pop music show *Countdown* presented its own annual awards ceremony, *Countdown* Music and Video Awards, which was co-produced by Carolyn James (also known as Carolyn Bailey) during 1981–1984 in collaboration with ARIA.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] ARIA provided peer voting for some awards, while *Countdown* provided coupons in the related *Countdown Magazine* for viewers to vote for populist awards.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] At the 1985 *Countdown* awards ceremony, held on 14 April 1986, fans of INXS and Uncanny X-Men scuffled during the broadcast and as a result ARIA decided to hold their own awards.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Since 2 March 1987, ARIA administered its own entirely peer-voted ARIA Music Awards, to "recognise excellence and innovation in all genres of Australian music" with an annual ceremony.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Initially included in the same awards ceremonies, it established the ARIA Hall of Fame in 1988 and has held separate annual ceremonies since 2005.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] The ARIA Hall of Fame "honours Australian musicians' achievements [that] have had a significant impact in Australia or around the world".
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] Like most recording industry associations, ARIA has been criticised for fighting copyright infringement matters aggressively, although in Australia this has largely taken the form of aggressive advertising campaigns particularly in cinemas directly preceding movies.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] This criticism is stauncher in Australia due to the absence of an equivalent Digital Millennium Copyright Act or state crimes acts which clearly establish copyright infringement as a crime.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] In February 2004, the Australian Record Industry Association (ARIA) took legal action against Kazaa, alleging copyright breaches.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] On 6 February 2005, the homes of two Sharman Networks executives and the offices of Sharman Networks in Australia were raided under a court order by ARIA to gather evidence for the trial.
[src:anindilyakwa-language/aria] ARIA has been criticised by former *Australian Idol* judge and record producer Ian Dickson for a perceived intolerance of *Australian Idol* contestants, and a lack of nomination in the ARIA Awards.
